          "Holdout Method",
          "Day 35\n{Accuracy: 0.6358 - ANN-LSTM, Precision: 0.75 - ANN-LSTM, Recall: 0.41 - ANN-LSTM, F1-Score: 0.52 - ANN-LSTM}\n\nDay 70\n{Accuracy: 0.6804 - ANN-LSTM, Precision: 0.80 - ANN-LSTM, Recall: 0.47 - ANN-LSTM, F1-Score: 0.58 - ANN-LSTM}\n\nDay 105\n{Accuracy: 0.6980 - ANN-LSTM, Precision: 0.81 - ANN-LSTM, Recall: 0.50 - ANN-LSTM, F1-Score: 0.61 - ANN-LSTM}\n\nDay 140\n{Accuracy: 0.7046 - ANN-LSTM, Precision: 0.80 - ANN-LSTM, Recall: 0.53 - ANN-LSTM, F1-Score: 0.64 - ANN-LSTM}\n\nDay 175\n{Accuracy: 0.7135 - ANN-LSTM, Precision: 0.81 - ANN-LSTM, Recall: 0.57 - ANN-LSTM, F1-Score: 0.67 - ANN-LSTM}",
          "In total, the authors perform 270 experiments. Each experiment relates to having one dataset starting at Day 1 and Finishing at each day throughout the course duration.\n\nAuthors show that model performance increases with longer datasets.\n\nAccuracy is computed for every day of prediction. Authors make 2 different sets of comparisons:\n\n1- ANN-LSTM vs other DL baselines - GRU and RNN, \n2. ANN - LSTM versus other State-of-the -art architectures: MLP, RF and AML.\n\nIn both scenarios, ANN-LSTM outperforms the other modells. ",
          "Holdout Method, \n\nComputational Times for Deep Learning, which hinders a model’s ability to be used as an EWS. "
        ]
      ],
